# Decor UI Library

Decor is a UI component library for Rails built on [Phlex](https://phlex.fun) and [Vident](https://github.com/stevegeek/vident). It ships with two visual skins so you can pick the one that fits each surface:

- **Daisy skin** (`Decor::Daisy::*`) — built on [daisyUI v5](https://daisyui.com), uses daisyUI's semantic color palette (primary / secondary / success / error / etc.) and themeable component classes. Adapts to any daisyUI theme without code changes. Generally a good fit for admin / internal UI.
- **Suite skin** (`Decor::Suite::*`) — bespoke design tokens (numbered shade scale, hairline borders, custom radii, motion durations, suite typography utilities). Generally a good fit for customer-facing UI that needs a distinct identity. See the [Design System](./02_design_system) page for the token catalogue.

Both skins share an abstract base under `Decor::Components::*` that owns the prop API; each concrete skin owns its visual language.

A small set of components are skinless because there's no visual divergence — `Decor::Icon` is the canonical example.

## Highlights

- Type-safe props via [Literal](https://literal.fun) — props declare their types at the class level and are enforced at instantiation.
- Stimulus integration via Vident — components declare controllers, targets, actions, values, outlets, and class maps with a single DSL.
- CSS prefix isolation — utilities are prefixed `decor:` and daisyUI components `decor:d-` so host's own Tailwind utilities never collide.
- Native browser APIs where possible — modals use the native `<dialog>` element, dropdowns use CSS anchor positioning + the Popover API.
- Security defaults — `href` props filter `javascript:` / `data:` / `vbscript:` schemes; modal `initial_content` only emits raw HTML when `html_safe?`; bulk-action forms inject CSRF tokens automatically.

## Quick usage

```ruby
# Daisy
render Decor::Daisy::Button.new(label: "Click me", color: :primary)

# Suite
render Decor::Suite::Button.new(label: "Click me", color: :primary, style: :filled)

# Skinless
render Decor::Icon.new(name: "star")
```

For the full per-component prop list, see the [Component Reference](./03_component_reference). For how to author your own components on top of Decor's base, see [Building Components](./04_building_components).

